{"title_page": "Canberra Plaza", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox shopping mall\n| name          = Canberra Plaza\n| image         = Picture of Canberra MRT and Canberra Plaza Model.jpg\n| caption       = Model picture showing Canberra Plaza with [[Canberra MRT station|Canberra MRT]]\n| location      = [[Sembawang]], [[Singapore]]\n| coordinates   = {{coord|1|26|35.724|N|103|49|49.663|E|region:SG|display=inline,title}}\n| address       = 133 Canberra View, Singapore 750133\n| opening_date  = 2020\n| developer     = [[Housing Development Board|Housing & Development Board]]\n| manager       = [[Knight Frank]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Housing & Development Board|title=Shops and Offices|url=http://www.hdb.gov.sg/cs/infoweb/business/commercial/renting-from-hdb/shops-offices|website=2018|accessdate=2018-04-13}}</ref>\n| owner         = [[Housing Development Board|Housing & Development Board]]\n| architect     = SAA Architects Pte. Ltd\n| floor_area    = {{convert|11000|m2|sqft}}(approximate)\n| floors        = 3 with 1 level basement\n| parking       = Provided (Under Construction)\n| publictransit = [[Canberra MRT station|{{SMRT code|NS|12}} Canberra]]<br>{{bus icon|12px}} 117, 169/169A, 883/883M<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mytransport.sg/content/mytransport/map.html?keyword=canberra%20link&from=menublockSearchByKeywords#|title=MyTransport.SG:Map|website=MyTransport.SG|access-date=2018-04-13}}</ref>\n| website       = [http://www.where2shop.sg/cs/w/CanberraPlaza Official Website]\n}}\n{{external media\n| float  = center\n| width  = 275px\n| image1 = [http://www.saagroup.com/wp/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/News-Flash-Sembawang_Web-1024x757@2x.jpg Artist Impression of the Canberra Plaza (Design Competition stage)] Source: SAA Architects\n}}\n\n'''Canberra Plaza''' is a future New Generation Neighbourhood Centre (NGNC) build by the [[Housing Development Board|Housing & Development Board]] (HDB), the government agency in charge of [[Public housing in Singapore|public housing development]] in [[Singapore]]. It is one of the new Neighbourhood Centres (NCs) being constructed by HDB in 10 years after the completion of [[Pioneer Mall]] and [[Punggol Plaza]] in 2004. [[Cable News Network (CNN)|CNN]] reported that Canberra Plaza will provide a \"complete live-work-play-learn environment for residents and signifies Singapore's public housing for the future\".<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" />\n\nThe 3-storey shopping centre is located in the eastern end of [[Sembawang]], [[Singapore]] as part of an upcoming [[Mixed-use development|mixed-use]] [[transit-oriented development]]. It was designed by a team led by SAA Architects. Construction started in mid-2015 and is expected to be completed and open in the late July 2020.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/hdb-builds-new-generation-neighbourhood-centres-upcoming-estates|title=HDB builds new generation neighbourhood centres for upcoming estates|work=TODAYonline|access-date=2018-04-13}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.hdb.gov.sg/cs/infoweb/press-releases/hdb-unveils-new-generation-of-neighbourhood-centres|title=HDB Unveils New Generation of Neighbourhood Centres - Housing & Development Board (HDB)|website=www.hdb.gov.sg|language=en|access-date=2018-04-13}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn 2004, with the completion of Pioneer Mall and Punggol Plaza, the Housing & Development Board (HDB) stopped building neighbourhood centres (NCs). This was an effort to get private sector developers to take over the construction of NCs in HDB towns.<ref name=\":1\" /> Some of the private NCs that were constructed include [[Seletar Mall]] (completed in 2014 by a [[Singapore Press Holdings|Singapore Press Holdings Limited]] (SPH) and United Engineers Limited joint venture).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theseletarmall.com/about|title=The Seletar Mall|website=www.theseletarmall.com|language=en|access-date=2018-05-03}}</ref>\n\nHowever, this caused much inconvenience for residents that moved into the newer towns early on as private developers normally constructed NCs only when a substantial catchment for a particular NC was present so as to generate enough revenue. In an attempt to alleviate these problems, HDB resumed the construction of NCs in 2014 after a 10-year break. These new NCs (one of which is Canberra Plaza) are known as '''N'''ew '''G'''eneration '''N'''eighbourhood '''C'''entre'''s''' ('''NGNCs''') and will each serve a neighbourhood with around 5000 to 6000 households.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThese NCs are called as such as they are improved versions of the past NCs. The NGNCs incorporated ideas obtained from public consultation while the older NCs do not. Each NGNC will also have a sheltered community plaza to host community events in order to foster social interaction within the community. Water features, terraces as well as \u201c[[environmentally friendly]]\u201d systems such as [[rainwater harvesting]] will also introduced in the NGNCs.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/hdb-builds-new-generation-neighbourhood-centres-for-upcoming-est-8244244|title=HDB builds new generation neighbourhood centres for upcoming estates|work=Channel NewsAsia|access-date=2018-04-13|language=en-US}}</ref> Cable News Network (CNN) further reported that Canberra Plaza will provide a \"complete live-work-play-learn environment for residents and signifies Singapore's public housing for the future\".<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2015/10/29/asia/singapore-public-housing/index.html|title=Luxury hotel? No, public housing, Singapore-style |first=Hilary |last=Whiteman|work=CNN|access-date=2018-04-13}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2015/10/29/asia/gallery/singapore-public-housing/index.html|title=Singapore's public housing for the future|website=CNN|access-date=2018-04-13}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, HDB held a competition to select the architectural team for Canberra Plaza. The [[design brief]] given was: \"design a mixed development with a [[gross floor area]] of {{convert|117000|m2|sqft}}.\" The Plaza was to be designed with a nautical theme inspired by flowing rivers, as the site of the Plaza is situated near [[canals]] such as [[Sungei Simpang Kiri]]. In addition, since the Plaza is situated at the gateway to Sembawang Neighbourhood 1, it should also serve as a distinctive landmark for the neighbourhood. In October, a team led by SAA Architects was announced as the winner of the competition.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.saagroup.com/saa-won-competition-to-design-sembawang-n1-c6-c12/|title=SAA Won Competition To Design Sembawang N1 C6 & C12 - SAA Group Architects|date=2014-10-01|work=SAA Group Architects|access-date=2018-04-13|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.where2shop.sg/cs/w/CanberraPlaza|title=Canberra Plaza - Where2Shop|website=www.where2shop.sg|language=en|access-date=2018-04-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180417001850/http://www.where2shop.sg/cs/w/CanberraPlaza|archive-date=2018-04-17|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOne year later, in October 2015, HDB held a public exhibition on Canberra Plaza (with an architectural model of the development) at the HDB Hub (HDB Headquarters) in [[Toa Payoh]]. Thereafter, construction of the Plaza commenced and was expected to end in 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/housing/hdb-unveils-next-gen-neighbourhood-centres-in-punggol-hougang-and-sembawang|title=HDB unveils next-gen neighbourhood centres in Punggol, Hougang and Sembawang|last=|date=2015-10-03|work=The Straits Times|access-date=2018-04-13|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/housing/hdb-to-build-4-next-gen-neighbourhood-centres|title=HDB to build 4 next-gen neighbourhood centres|last=Janice Heng|date=2015-10-04|work=The Straits Times|access-date=2018-04-13|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Locality ==\n\nCanberra Plaza is located in the northern part of Sembawang and is part of an upcoming mixed-use transit-oriented development. Around the Plaza are new and upcoming HDB [[Public housing in Singapore|public housing]] developments (which forms Sembawang Neighbourhood 1), private [[condominium]]s as well as [[landed property|landed properties]] (Sembawang Springs Estate). Also in the vicinity is [[Yishun]] Industrial Park A which mainly comprises [[workshop]]s of [[manufacturing]] businesses as well as [[automobile repair shop]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jtc.gov.sg/industrial-land-and-space/Pages/yishun-industrial-park-a.aspx|title=Yishun Industrial Park A|website=JTC Corporation|access-date=2018-05-01}}</ref> In addition, the Singapore [[Subsidiary|subsidiaries]] of [[multinational corporation]]s such as [[Murata Manufacturing]] and ASM Assembly Systems are located within the industrial park.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.murata.com/en-sg/about/asean/singapore|title=About Murata Singapore {{!}} Murata Manufacturing Co., Ltd.|website=www.murata.com|language=en-SG|access-date=2018-05-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.asm-smt.com/en/asm-directions|title=ASM Assembly Systems GmbH & Co. KG - Directions to the ASM Assembly Systems locations|last=Nailer|first=Jon|website=www.asm-smt.com|access-date=2018-05-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180501162203/http://www.asm-smt.com/en/asm-directions|archive-date=2018-05-01|url-status=dead}}</ref> The [[Singapore Civil Defence Force]] [[Singapore Civil Defence Force#Operational divisions|3rd Division Headquarters]] (co-located within Yishun Fire Station) and [[Migrant worker#Singapore|foreign migrant workers]] [[Dormitory#Company dormitories|dormitories]] (Simpang Lodges 1 & 2) are located nearby.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sl2dormitory.com/|title=:: Simpang Lodge 2|website=www.sl2dormitory.com|access-date=2018-05-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scdf.gov.sg/home/about-us/organisation-structure/scdf-division-hq/3rd-scdf-div-hq|title=3rd SCDF DIV HQ|website=www.scdf.gov.sg|language=en|access-date=2018-05-05}}</ref>\n\n== Layout ==\nCanberra Plaza is designed with three commercial stories that have a combined gross floor area of {{convert|11000|m2|sqft}} The main anchor tenants are expected to be a [[supermarket]] and [[food court]]s. Other commercial units will include [[restaurant]]s, enrichment centres as well as [[clinic]]s. A sheltered plaza for community activities and a water playground is incorporated into the design of Canberra Plaza as well. In order to improve connectivity, a portion of the [[Storey#East Asian schemes|ground level]] will be kept open for 24-hours and an sheltered elevated pedestrian [[footbridge]] will also link housing precincts (such as Eastlink II @ Canberra) across Canberra Way to Canberra Plaza. A similar footbridge will connect Canberra Plaza to [[Canberra MRT station]] which is located across Canberra Link.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>[http://www20.hdb.gov.sg/fi10/fi10297p.nsf/ImageView/futurehomes2015/$file/Panel+9.pdf Exhibition panel for Canberra Plaza at the exhibition](PDF), Retrieved 2018-04-18. Source: HDB</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Award\n!Awarding Agency\n!Ref.\n|-\n|'''2017'''\n|BCA Green Mark Platinum Award (Category: Buildings)\n|[[Building and Construction Authority|Building & Construction Authority of Singapore]] (BCA)\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bca.gov.sg/greenMark/others/gm2017.pdf|title=GM2017.pdf|last=Building & Construction Authority of Singapore|page=57|access-date=2018-04-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bca.gov.sg/greenmark/green_mark_buildings.html|title=About BCA Green Mark Scheme|last=Building and Construction Authority|access-date=2018-04-14}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20180417001850/http://www.where2shop.sg/cs/w/CanberraPlaza  Canberra Plaza] - [https://web.archive.org/web/20180429091714/http://www.where2shop.sg/cs/w/Home Where2Shop] (HDB Page for HDB Neighbourhood Centres)\n*{{commons-inline|Canberra Plaza}} - More pictures of Archietectural Model\n\n{{Singapore malls}}\n\n[[Category:Shopping malls in Singapore]]\n[[Category:Places in Singapore]]\n[[Category:Sembawang]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox shopping mall\n| name          = Canberra Plaza\n| image         = Picture of Canberra MRT and Canberra Plaza Model.jpg\n| caption       = Model picture showing Canberra Plaza with [[Canberra MRT station|Canberra MRT]]\n| location      = [[Sembawang]], [[Singapore]]\n| coordinates   = {{coord|1|26|35.724|N|103|49|49.663|E|region:SG|display=inline,title}}\n| address       = 133 Canberra View, Singapore 750133\n| opening_date  = 2020\n| developer     = [[Housing Development Board|Housing & Development Board]]\n| manager       = [[Knight Frank]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Housing & Development Board|title=Shops and Offices|url=http://www.hdb.gov.sg/cs/infoweb/business/commercial/renting-from-hdb/shops-offices|website=2018|accessdate=2018-04-13}}</ref>\n| owner         = [[Housing Development Board|Housing & Development Board]]\n| architect     = SAA Architects Pte. Ltd\n| floor_area    = {{convert|11000|m2|sqft}}(approximate)\n| floors        = 3 with 1 level basement\n| parking       = Provided (Under Construction)\n| publictransit = [[Canberra MRT station|{{SMRT code|NS|12}} Canberra]]<br>{{bus icon|12px}} 117, 169/169A, 883/883M<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mytransport.sg/content/mytransport/map.html?keyword=canberra%20link&from=menublockSearchByKeywords#|title=MyTransport.SG:Map|website=MyTransport.SG|access-date=2018-04-13}}</ref>\n| website       = [http://www.where2shop.sg/cs/w/CanberraPlaza Official Website]\n}}\n{{external media\n| float  = center\n| width  = 275px\n| image1 = [http://www.saagroup.com/wp/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/News-Flash-Sembawang_Web-1024x757@2x.jpg Artist Impression of the Canberra Plaza (Design Competition stage)] Source: SAA Architects\n}}\n\n'''Canberra Plaza''' is a future New Generation Neighbourhood Centre (NGNC) build by the [[Housing Development Board|Housing & Development Board]] (HDB), the government agency in charge of [[Public housing in Singapore|public housing development]] in [[Singapore]]. It is one of the new Neighbourhood Centres (NCs) being constructed by HDB in 10 years after the completion of [[Pioneer Mall]] and [[Punggol Plaza]] in 2004. [[Cable News Network (CNN)|CNN]] reported that Canberra Plaza will provide a \"complete live-work-play-learn environment for residents and signifies Singapore's public housing for the future\".<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" />\n\nThe 3-storey shopping centre is located in the eastern end of [[Sembawang]], [[Singapore]] as part of an upcoming [[Mixed-use development|mixed-use]] [[transit-oriented development]]. It was designed by a team led by SAA Architects. Construction started in mid-2015 and was expected to be completed in 2019.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/hdb-builds-new-generation-neighbourhood-centres-for-upcoming-est-8244244|title=HDB builds new generation neighbourhood centres for upcoming estates|work=Channel NewsAsia|access-date=2018-04-13|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/hdb-builds-new-generation-neighbourhood-centres-upcoming-estates|title=HDB builds new generation neighbourhood centres for upcoming estates|work=TODAYonline|access-date=2018-04-13}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.hdb.gov.sg/cs/infoweb/press-releases/hdb-unveils-new-generation-of-neighbourhood-centres|title=HDB Unveils New Generation of Neighbourhood Centres - Housing & Development Board (HDB)|website=www.hdb.gov.sg|language=en|access-date=2018-04-13}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn 2004, with the completion of Pioneer Mall and Punggol Plaza, the Housing & Development Board (HDB) stopped building neighbourhood centres (NCs). This was an effort to get private sector developers to take over the construction of NCs in HDB towns.<ref name=\":1\" /> Some of the private NCs that were constructed include [[Seletar Mall]] (completed in 2014 by a [[Singapore Press Holdings|Singapore Press Holdings Limited]] (SPH) and United Engineers Limited joint venture).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theseletarmall.com/about|title=The Seletar Mall|website=www.theseletarmall.com|language=en|access-date=2018-05-03}}</ref>\n\nHowever, this caused much inconvenience for residents that moved into the newer towns early on as private developers normally constructed NCs only when a substantial catchment for a particular NC was present so as to generate enough revenue. In an attempt to alleviate these problems, HDB resumed the construction of NCs in 2014 after a 10-year break. These new NCs (one of which is Canberra Plaza) are known as '''N'''ew '''G'''eneration '''N'''eighbourhood '''C'''entre'''s''' ('''NGNCs''') and will each serve a neighbourhood with around 5000 to 6000 households.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThese NCs are called as such as they are improved versions of the past NCs. The NGNCs incorporated ideas obtained from public consultation while the older NCs do not. Each NGNC will also have a sheltered community plaza to host community events in order to foster social interaction within the community. Water features, terraces as well as \u201c[[environmentally friendly]]\u201d systems such as [[rainwater harvesting]] will also introduced in the NGNCs.<ref name=\":0\" /> Cable News Network (CNN) further reported that Canberra Plaza will provide a \"complete live-work-play-learn environment for residents and signifies Singapore's public housing for the future\".<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2015/10/29/asia/singapore-public-housing/index.html|title=Luxury hotel? No, public housing, Singapore-style |first=Hilary |last=Whiteman|work=CNN|access-date=2018-04-13}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2015/10/29/asia/gallery/singapore-public-housing/index.html|title=Singapore's public housing for the future|website=CNN|access-date=2018-04-13}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, HDB held a competition to select the architectural team for Canberra Plaza. The [[design brief]] given was: \"design a mixed development with a [[gross floor area]] of {{convert|117000|m2|sqft}}.\" The Plaza was to be designed with a nautical theme inspired by flowing rivers, as the site of the Plaza is situated near [[canals]] such as [[Sungei Simpang Kiri]]. In addition, since the Plaza is situated at the gateway to Sembawang Neighbourhood 1, it should also serve as a distinctive landmark for the neighbourhood. In October, a team led by SAA Architects was announced as the winner of the competition.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.saagroup.com/saa-won-competition-to-design-sembawang-n1-c6-c12/|title=SAA Won Competition To Design Sembawang N1 C6 & C12 - SAA Group Architects|date=2014-10-01|work=SAA Group Architects|access-date=2018-04-13|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.where2shop.sg/cs/w/CanberraPlaza|title=Canberra Plaza - Where2Shop|website=www.where2shop.sg|language=en|access-date=2018-04-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180417001850/http://www.where2shop.sg/cs/w/CanberraPlaza|archive-date=2018-04-17|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOne year later, in October 2015, HDB held a public exhibition on Canberra Plaza (with an architectural model of the development) at the HDB Hub (HDB Headquarters) in [[Toa Payoh]]. Thereafter, construction of the Plaza commenced and was expected to end in 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/housing/hdb-unveils-next-gen-neighbourhood-centres-in-punggol-hougang-and-sembawang|title=HDB unveils next-gen neighbourhood centres in Punggol, Hougang and Sembawang|last=|date=2015-10-03|work=The Straits Times|access-date=2018-04-13|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/housing/hdb-to-build-4-next-gen-neighbourhood-centres|title=HDB to build 4 next-gen neighbourhood centres|last=Janice Heng|date=2015-10-04|work=The Straits Times|access-date=2018-04-13|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Locality ==\n\nCanberra Plaza is located in the northern part of Sembawang and is part of an upcoming mixed-use transit-oriented development. Around the Plaza are new and upcoming HDB [[Public housing in Singapore|public housing]] developments (which forms Sembawang Neighbourhood 1), private [[condominium]]s as well as [[landed property|landed properties]] (Sembawang Springs Estate). Also in the vicinity is [[Yishun]] Industrial Park A which mainly comprises [[workshop]]s of [[manufacturing]] businesses as well as [[automobile repair shop]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jtc.gov.sg/industrial-land-and-space/Pages/yishun-industrial-park-a.aspx|title=Yishun Industrial Park A|website=JTC Corporation|access-date=2018-05-01}}</ref> In addition, the Singapore [[Subsidiary|subsidiaries]] of [[multinational corporation]]s such as [[Murata Manufacturing]] and ASM Assembly Systems are located within the industrial park.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.murata.com/en-sg/about/asean/singapore|title=About Murata Singapore {{!}} Murata Manufacturing Co., Ltd.|website=www.murata.com|language=en-SG|access-date=2018-05-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.asm-smt.com/en/asm-directions|title=ASM Assembly Systems GmbH & Co. KG - Directions to the ASM Assembly Systems locations|last=Nailer|first=Jon|website=www.asm-smt.com|access-date=2018-05-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180501162203/http://www.asm-smt.com/en/asm-directions|archive-date=2018-05-01|url-status=dead}}</ref> The [[Singapore Civil Defence Force]] [[Singapore Civil Defence Force#Operational divisions|3rd Division Headquarters]] (co-located within Yishun Fire Station) and [[Migrant worker#Singapore|foreign migrant workers]] [[Dormitory#Company dormitories|dormitories]] (Simpang Lodges 1 & 2) are located nearby.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sl2dormitory.com/|title=:: Simpang Lodge 2|website=www.sl2dormitory.com|access-date=2018-05-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scdf.gov.sg/home/about-us/organisation-structure/scdf-division-hq/3rd-scdf-div-hq|title=3rd SCDF DIV HQ|website=www.scdf.gov.sg|language=en|access-date=2018-05-05}}</ref>\n\n== Layout ==\nCanberra Plaza is designed with three commercial stories that have a combined gross floor area of {{convert|11000|m2|sqft}} The main anchor tenants are expected to be a [[supermarket]] and [[food court]]s. Other commercial units will include [[restaurant]]s, enrichment centres as well as [[clinic]]s. A sheltered plaza for community activities and a water playground is incorporated into the design of Canberra Plaza as well. In order to improve connectivity, a portion of the [[Storey#East Asian schemes|ground level]] will be kept open for 24-hours and an sheltered elevated pedestrian [[footbridge]] will also link housing precincts (such as Eastlink II @ Canberra) across Canberra Way to Canberra Plaza. A similar footbridge will connect Canberra Plaza to [[Canberra MRT station]] which is located across Canberra Link.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>[http://www20.hdb.gov.sg/fi10/fi10297p.nsf/ImageView/futurehomes2015/$file/Panel+9.pdf Exhibition panel for Canberra Plaza at the exhibition](PDF), Retrieved 2018-04-18. Source: HDB</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Award\n!Awarding Agency\n!Ref.\n|-\n|'''2017'''\n|BCA Green Mark Platinum Award (Category: Buildings)\n|[[Building and Construction Authority|Building & Construction Authority of Singapore]] (BCA)\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bca.gov.sg/greenMark/others/gm2017.pdf|title=GM2017.pdf|last=Building & Construction Authority of Singapore|page=57|access-date=2018-04-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bca.gov.sg/greenmark/green_mark_buildings.html|title=About BCA Green Mark Scheme|last=Building and Construction Authority|access-date=2018-04-14}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20180417001850/http://www.where2shop.sg/cs/w/CanberraPlaza  Canberra Plaza] - [https://web.archive.org/web/20180429091714/http://www.where2shop.sg/cs/w/Home Where2Shop] (HDB Page for HDB Neighbourhood Centres)\n*{{commons-inline|Canberra Plaza}} - More pictures of Archietectural Model\n\n{{Singapore malls}}\n\n[[Category:Shopping malls in Singapore]]\n[[Category:Places in Singapore]]\n[[Category:Sembawang]]\n", "name_user": "KieronKN", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canberra_Plaza"}
{"title_page": "Mocking of Jesus", "text_new": "[[File:Mathis Gothart Gr\u00fcnewald 062.jpg|thumb|200px|''[[The Mocking of Christ (Gr\u00fcnewald)|The Mocking of Christ]]'' by [[Matthias Gr\u00fcnewald]], c. 1505]]\nThe '''mocking of Jesus''' occurred several times, after his [[Sanhedrin trial of Jesus|trial]] and before his [[Crucifixion of Jesus|crucifixion]] according to the [[canonical gospel]]s of the New Testament. It is considered part of Jesus' [[Passion (Christianity)|passion]].\n\nAccording to the gospel narratives, [[Jesus]] had [[Jesus predicts his death|predicted]] that he would be mocked (Matthew 20:19, Mark 10:34, and Luke 18:32). The mocking of Christ took place in three stages: immediately following his trial, immediately following his condemnation by [[Pontius Pilate]], and when he was being crucified.\n\nThe New Testament narratives of Jesus being mocked are filled with [[irony]], while the mockery focuses on Jesus' prophetic and kingly roles.<ref>Larry Chouinard, [https://books.google.com/books?id=uSuWJVwYxPAC&pg=PA487 Matthew] (1997), p. 487.</ref><ref>David L. Tiede, [https://books.google.com/books?id=G8D_zbAOXMoC&pg=PA398 Luke] (1988), p. 398.</ref>\n\n==First stage==\n[[File:WLA lacma The Mocking of Christ.jpg|thumb|left|[[Gerrit van Honthorst]], ''The Mocking of Christ'', c. 1617]]\nAfter Jesus' [[Sanhedrin trial of Jesus|condemnation by the Sanhedrin]], some spat on him (Mark 14:65). He was blindfolded and beaten, and then mocked: \"Prophesy! Who hit you?\" (Luke 22:63). This was done by those men who \"held Jesus\" (Luke 22:63, [[KJV|King James Version]]). The [[New International Version]] translates this as \"the men who were guarding Jesus\", but [[Joel B. Green]] takes the phrase to refer to the \"Chief priests, the officers of the temple police, and the elders\" mentioned in verse 52.<ref name=Green />\n\nGreen suggests that Jesus suffers the mockery that is typical of prophets, and that his suffering suggests his \"solidarity with God's agents who speak on God's behalf and are rejected.\"<ref name=Green>[[Joel B. Green]], ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=wzRVN2S8cVgC&pg=PA789 The Gospel of Luke]'' (1997), p. 789.</ref> Susan R. Garrett sees Mark's inclusion of the mockery as an example of irony, since Jesus is indeed a [[prophet]], at the very moment his prophecy that [[Denial of Peter|Peter would deny him]] was being fulfilled.<ref>Susan R. Garrett, [https://books.google.com/books?id=ycCaqeuxVJEC&pg=PA118 The Temptations of Jesus in Mark's Gospel] (1998), p. 118.</ref> The prophetic assignment is not always portrayed as positive in the Bible,<ref>Commentary on Jeremiah, The Jewish Study Bible, Oxford University Press, 2004</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Isaiah (Commentary), [[John Goldingay]], Hendrickson, 2001</ref><ref>Commentary on Isaiah 6:8-13, The Jewish Study Bible, Oxford University Press, 2004</ref> and prophets were often the target of persecution and opposition.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">\u2019\u2019Jeremiah (Prophet)\u2019\u2019, The Anchor Bible Dictionary Volume 3, Doubleday, 1992</ref>\n\n==Second stage==\n[[File:Jesus Mocked by the Soldiers.jpg|thumb|[[\u00c9douard Manet]], ''Jesus Mocked by the Soldiers'', c. 1865]]\nAfter his condemnation by [[Pontius Pilate]], Jesus was [[Flagellation of Christ|flogged]] and mocked by [[Legionary|Roman soldiers]]. They clothed him with a \"purple\" ({{bibleverse|Mark|15:17|KJV}}) or \"scarlet\" ({{bibleverse|Matthew|27:28|KJV}}) robe symbolizing a royal gown since purple was a [[Tyrian purple|royal color]], put a [[crown of thorns]] on his head symbolizing a royal crown, and put a staff in his hand symbolizing a scepter. They knelt before him and said, \"Hail, king of the Jews!\" ({{bibleverse|Matthew|27:29|KJV}}). This was done as a mockery of Jesus' kingship. After this, they spat on him, sodomized his anus, and struck him on the head with the staff repeatedly.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Matthew+27|title=Matthew 27 |publisher=Bible Gateway|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[Peter Leithart]] notes that at the end of the scene, the soldiers \"reverse the whole coronation with an anti-coronation.  They spit in contempt instead of kneeling in reverence, pull the scepter from Jesus\u2019 hand and beat His crowned head with it, strip off the scarlet robe and replace it with Jesus\u2019 own robe.\" Leithart goes on to suggest that, at this point, the Romans \"remove the veil of irony and reveal what they really think\" about the Jews and their God. <ref name=Leithart>[[Peter Leithart]], [http://www.credenda.org/index.php/Church/god-is-mocked.html God is Mocked], [[Credenda/Agenda]].</ref> The crowning/de-crowning of a mock king is what [[Mikhail Bakhtin]] calls the \"[[carnivalesque]].\" Carnivalesque expresses \u201clife drawn out of its usual rut\u201d and \u201cthe reverse side of the world (''monde \u00e0 l\u2019envers'')\" in which normally suppressed voices of the culture mock everyday social hierarchies and the voices of the status quo.<ref> [[Mikhail Bakhtin]],  ''Problems of Dostoevsky\u2019s Poetics''. Theory and History of Literature, Vol. 8. Ed. and trans. by Caryl Emerson. (Minneapolis, MN: University of Minnesota Press, 1984), 122.</ref>  The soldiers not only mock Jesus; they mock the whole notion of kingship modeled on this world. The irony is rich because the type of king they mock\u2014one who lords over others with scepter, crown, and robe\u2014is not the type of king Jesus is or the type of kingdom he brings (cf. Mark 10:45 and [[Son of man came to serve]]). Their mockery speaks truth beyond what they could possibly know.<ref>[[James L. Resseguie]], \"[https://www.mdpi.com/2077-1444/10/3/217 A Glossary of New Testament Narrative Criticism with Illustrations,\"] in ''Religions'', 10 (3) 217), 3-4.</ref> \n\nRobert J. Miller suggests that the gospel account is deeply [[irony|ironic]] since Jesus is exercising his kingship through submission and suffering: \"the Roman [[Legionary|legionnaires]] have unwittingly furthered God's secret purposes by dressing Jesus up as a king.\"<ref>Robert J. Miller, ''The Complete Gospels'' (1994), p. 50</ref> In fact, the irony operates on two levels. [[James L. Resseguie]] points out that there is [[verbal irony]] in the way the soldiers \"mock Jesus as a dismal failure and a pretend king\" (that is, the soldiers are themselves being ironic) as well as [[dramatic irony]] in that the readers \"know that the acclamation rings true in ways that the soldiers could not possibly understand.\"<ref>[[James L. Resseguie]], [https://books.google.com/books?id=8JOdz84lmUQC&pg=PA74 Narrative Criticism of the New Testament: An Introduction] (2005), p. 74; see also \"A Glossary of New Testament Narrative Criticism with Illustrations, https://www.mdpi.com/2077-1444/10/3/217. </ref>  Luke 23:11 also mentions that \"[[Herod Antipas|Herod]] and his soldiers ridiculed and mocked him\" ([[New Revised Standard Version]]).\n\n==Third stage==\n[[File:Hendrick ter Brugghen - Die Verspottung Christi.jpg|thumb|left|[[Hendrick ter Brugghen]], ''The Mocking of Christ'', c. 1625]]\nJesus was also mocked while he was [[Crucifixion of Jesus|on the cross]]. According to Mark 15:29-30, this was done by those who passed by and hurled insults at him and told him to come down from the cross.  Mark 15:31-32 points out that \"the chief priests and the teachers of the law\" also mocked him among themselves, saying: \"He saved others, but he can\u2019t save himself! Let this Messiah, this king of Israel, come down now from the cross, that we may see and believe.\" Finally, those crucified with Jesus also heaped insults at him (Mark 15:32). \n\nLuke 23:36-37 mentions mocking by Roman soldiers: \"The soldiers also mocked him, coming up and offering him sour wine, and saying, 'If you are the King of the Jews, save yourself!'\" ([[New Revised Standard Version]]). In Matthew 27:42 people, priest and the elders mock Jesus, and shout at him while he is hanging on the cross: \"He saved others; let Him save Himself if He is the Christ, the chosen of God.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://biblehub.com/matthew/27-42.htm|title= Matthew 27:42|publisher=Bible Hub|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Luke 23:39, one criminal on his left who hung there together with Jesus on the cross, hurled insults at Jesus: \"Aren't you the Messiah? Save yourself and us!\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Luke+23|title=The Crucifixion of Jesus, Luke 23 |publisher=Bible Gateway|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nThus, whereas the first stage involves mockery by Jews, and the second stage mockery by gentiles, the third stage has both together.<ref>[[Klaas Schilder]], ''Christ on Trial'' (1939), p. 177.</ref> Leithart notes that at this point \"Jews and Gentiles, governors and criminals, scribes and commoners, all humanity joins in a single chorus of blasphemy.\"<ref name=Leithart />\n\nTimothy C. Gray notes that in the Gospel of Mark, the mocking of Jesus on the cross \"takes up the two charges leveled against Jesus at his trial\": firstly, that Jesus \"threatened the temple with destruction\" (14:58 and 15:29); secondly, that Jesus \"claimed to be the Messiah\" (14:61-62 and 15:31-32).<ref>Timothy C. Gray, ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=IINN-m6YIGMC&pg=PA181 The Temple in the Gospel of Mark: A Study in Its Narrative Role]'' (2008), p. 181.</ref>  {{Clear}}\n\n==Theological significance==\n[[File:Mateo Cerezo d. J. 001.jpg|thumb|upright=0.1|[[Mateo Cerezo]], ''[[Ecce Homo]]'', 1650]]\n{{Death of Jesus}}\n\n[[Peter Leithart]] argues that in the person of Jesus, God himself was mocked. He suggests that \"for Matthew, the cross is mainly about man\u2019s mockery of God,\" and notes that while Paul says in [[Epistle to the Galatians|Galatians]] 6:7 that \"God is not mocked\", this is precisely because God ''has'' been mocked.<ref name=Leithart />\n\nMany Christians see Jesus' suffering as being [[Redemption (theology)|redemptive]]. Francis Foulkes argues that the emphasis in the New Testament is on Jesus' suffering and death being \"for us\".<ref>Francis Foulkes, [http://www.biblestudytools.com/dictionaries/bakers-evangelical-dictionary/death-of-christ.html Death of Christ], ''Baker's Evangelical Dictionary of Biblical Theology''.</ref> In this way, some Christians see the mockery that Jesus endured as being borne on their behalf. For example, [[Philip Bliss]] wrote in his hymn, \"Hallelujah! What a Savior\":\n<blockquote><poem>\nBearing shame and scoffing rude,\nIn my place condemned He stood;\nSealed my pardon with His blood.\nHallelujah! What a Savior!<ref>[http://www.hymntime.com/tch/htm/h/a/l/halwasav.htm The Cyber Hymnal: ''Hallelujah! What a Savior'']</ref>\n</poem></blockquote>\n\nThe mockery of Jesus is also seen by many Christians in the servant songs,  such as in Isaiah 50:6  where \n<blockquote><poem>\nI gave my back to those who strike,\nand my cheeks to those who pull out the beard;\nI hid not my face  from disgrace and spitting.\n</poem></blockquote>\n\nWhich is in remarkable contrast with the forward looking following verse, Isaiah 50:7\n<blockquote><poem>\nBecause the Sovereign Lord helps me,\nI will not be disgraced.\nTherefore have I set my face like flint,\nand I know I will not be put to shame.\n</poem></blockquote>\n\nThe scene when Jesus was mocked while he was on the cross, is also a manifestation of the mercy of God through Jesus, who himself is mocked, humiliated and in pain. Two men were crucified at the same time as Jesus, one on his right hand and one on his left ({{Bibleverse||Matthew|27:38|KJV}}, {{Bibleverse||Mark|15:27-28,32|KJV}}, {{Bibleverse||Luke|23:33|KJV}}, {{Bibleverse||John|19:18|KJV}}), which [[Gospel of Mark|Mark]] interprets as fulfillment of the [[prophecy]] of [[Isaiah]] {{Bibleverse-nb||Isaiah|53:12|HE}}. According to [[Gospel of Matthew|Matthew]] and Mark, respectively, both of the \"thieves\" mocked Jesus ({{Bibleverse||Matthew|27:44|KJV}}, {{Bibleverse||Mark|15:32|KJV}}); Luke however, mentions that:\n<blockquote>\n<sup>39</sup> Now one of the criminals hanging there reviled Jesus, saying, \"Are you not the Messiah? Save yourself and us.\"\n<sup>40</sup> The other, however, rebuking him, said in reply, \"Have you no fear of God, for you are subject to the same condemnation?\n<sup>41</sup> And indeed, we have been condemned justly, for the sentence we received corresponds to our crimes, but this man has done nothing criminal.\"\n<sup>42</sup> Then he said, \"Jesus, remember me when you come into your kingdom.\"\n<sup>43</sup> He replied to him, \"Amen I say to you today you will be with me in Paradise.\" {{Bibleverse-nb||Luke|23:39-43|NIV}}\n</blockquote>\n\nJesus promised to [[Penitent thief|this thief]] that he will be with him in the Paradise, right in front of those who were mocking him. God saves through Jesus, because God is full of mercy, a mercy revealed through Jesus Christ, that says to a thief: \"Today you will be with me in Paradise.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.beliefnet.com/columnists/markdroberts/2007/04/the-eleventh-station-jesus-promises-his-kingdom-to-the-good-thief.html|title=The Eleventh Station: Jesus Promises His Kingdom to the Good Thief|publisher=Beliefnet|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Flagellation of Christ]]\n*[[Crown of thorns]]\n*[[Ecce homo]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite journal |last=Pejovi\u0107 |first=Roksanda |title=The Mocking of Christ and other scenes from the cycle of <i>The sufferings of Christ</i> as illustrated by musical instruments in southern-European art |journal=New Sound |issue=2 |date=1993 |pages=71\u201393 |issn=0354-818X }}\n* {{cite journal |last=Ballester |first=Jordi |title=Trumpets, Heralds and Minstrels: Their relation to the Image of Power and Representation in the Fourteenth- and Fifteenth-Century Catalano-Aragonese Painting |journal=Music in Art |volume=43 |issue=1\u20132 |date=2018 |pages=5\u201319 |issn=1522-7464 }}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline|Mocking of Christ}}\n\n[[Category:Passion of Jesus]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Mathis Gothart Gr\u00fcnewald 062.jpg|thumb|200px|''[[The Mocking of Christ (Gr\u00fcnewald)|The Mocking of Christ]]'' by [[Matthias Gr\u00fcnewald]], c. 1505]]\nThe '''mocking of Jesus''' occurred several times, after his [[Sanhedrin trial of Jesus|trial]] and before his [[Crucifixion of Jesus|crucifixion]] according to the [[canonical gospel]]s of the New Testament. It is considered part of Jesus' [[Passion (Christianity)|passion]].\n\nAccording to the gospel narratives, [[Jesus]] had [[Jesus predicts his death|predicted]] that he would be mocked (Matthew 20:19, Mark 10:34, and Luke 18:32). The mocking of Christ took place in three stages: immediately following his trial, immediately following his condemnation by [[Pontius Pilate]], and when he was being crucified.\n\nThe New Testament narratives of Jesus being mocked are filled with [[irony]], while the mockery focuses on Jesus' prophetic and kingly roles.<ref>Larry Chouinard, [https://books.google.com/books?id=uSuWJVwYxPAC&pg=PA487 Matthew] (1997), p. 487.</ref><ref>David L. Tiede, [https://books.google.com/books?id=G8D_zbAOXMoC&pg=PA398 Luke] (1988), p. 398.</ref>\n\n==First stage==\n[[File:WLA lacma The Mocking of Christ.jpg|thumb|left|[[Gerrit van Honthorst]], ''The Mocking of Christ'', c. 1617]]\nAfter Jesus' [[Sanhedrin trial of Jesus|condemnation by the Sanhedrin]], some spat on him (Mark 14:65). He was blindfolded and beaten, and then mocked: \"Prophesy! Who hit you?\" (Luke 22:63). This was done by those men who \"held Jesus\" (Luke 22:63, [[KJV|King James Version]]). The [[New International Version]] translates this as \"the men who were guarding Jesus\", but [[Joel B. Green]] takes the phrase to refer to the \"Chief priests, the officers of the temple police, and the elders\" mentioned in verse 52.<ref name=Green />\n\nGreen suggests that Jesus suffers the mockery that is typical of prophets, and that his suffering suggests his \"solidarity with God's agents who speak on God's behalf and are rejected.\"<ref name=Green>[[Joel B. Green]], ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=wzRVN2S8cVgC&pg=PA789 The Gospel of Luke]'' (1997), p. 789.</ref> Susan R. Garrett sees Mark's inclusion of the mockery as an example of irony, since Jesus is indeed a [[prophet]], at the very moment his prophecy that [[Denial of Peter|Peter would deny him]] was being fulfilled.<ref>Susan R. Garrett, [https://books.google.com/books?id=ycCaqeuxVJEC&pg=PA118 The Temptations of Jesus in Mark's Gospel] (1998), p. 118.</ref> The prophetic assignment is not always portrayed as positive in the Bible,<ref>Commentary on Jeremiah, The Jewish Study Bible, Oxford University Press, 2004</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Isaiah (Commentary), [[John Goldingay]], Hendrickson, 2001</ref><ref>Commentary on Isaiah 6:8-13, The Jewish Study Bible, Oxford University Press, 2004</ref> and prophets were often the target of persecution and opposition.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">\u2019\u2019Jeremiah (Prophet)\u2019\u2019, The Anchor Bible Dictionary Volume 3, Doubleday, 1992</ref>\n\n==Second stage==\n[[File:Jesus Mocked by the Soldiers.jpg|thumb|[[\u00c9douard Manet]], ''Jesus Mocked by the Soldiers'', c. 1865]]\nAfter his condemnation by [[Pontius Pilate]], Jesus was [[Flagellation of Christ|flogged]] and mocked by [[Legionary|Roman soldiers]]. They clothed him with a \"purple\" ({{bibleverse|Mark|15:17|KJV}}) or \"scarlet\" ({{bibleverse|Matthew|27:28|KJV}}) robe symbolizing a royal gown since purple was a [[Tyrian purple|royal color]], put a [[crown of thorns]] on his head symbolizing a royal crown, and put a staff in his hand symbolizing a scepter. They knelt before him and said, \"Hail, king of the Jews!\" ({{bibleverse|Matthew|27:29|KJV}}). This was done as a mockery of Jesus' kingship. After this, they spat on him, and struck him on the head with the staff repeatedly.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Matthew+27|title=Matthew 27 |publisher=Bible Gateway|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[Peter Leithart]] notes that at the end of the scene, the soldiers \"reverse the whole coronation with an anti-coronation.  They spit in contempt instead of kneeling in reverence, pull the scepter from Jesus\u2019 hand and beat His crowned head with it, strip off the scarlet robe and replace it with Jesus\u2019 own robe.\" Leithart goes on to suggest that, at this point, the Romans \"remove the veil of irony and reveal what they really think\" about the Jews and their God. <ref name=Leithart>[[Peter Leithart]], [http://www.credenda.org/index.php/Church/god-is-mocked.html God is Mocked], [[Credenda/Agenda]].</ref> The crowning/de-crowning of a mock king is what [[Mikhail Bakhtin]] calls the \"[[carnivalesque]].\" Carnivalesque expresses \u201clife drawn out of its usual rut\u201d and \u201cthe reverse side of the world (''monde \u00e0 l\u2019envers'')\" in which normally suppressed voices of the culture mock everyday social hierarchies and the voices of the status quo.<ref> [[Mikhail Bakhtin]],  ''Problems of Dostoevsky\u2019s Poetics''. Theory and History of Literature, Vol. 8. Ed. and trans. by Caryl Emerson. (Minneapolis, MN: University of Minnesota Press, 1984), 122.</ref>  The soldiers not only mock Jesus; they mock the whole notion of kingship modeled on this world. The irony is rich because the type of king they mock\u2014one who lords over others with scepter, crown, and robe\u2014is not the type of king Jesus is or the type of kingdom he brings (cf. Mark 10:45 and [[Son of man came to serve]]). Their mockery speaks truth beyond what they could possibly know.<ref>[[James L. Resseguie]], \"[https://www.mdpi.com/2077-1444/10/3/217 A Glossary of New Testament Narrative Criticism with Illustrations,\"] in ''Religions'', 10 (3) 217), 3-4.</ref> \n\nRobert J. Miller suggests that the gospel account is deeply [[irony|ironic]] since Jesus is exercising his kingship through submission and suffering: \"the Roman [[Legionary|legionnaires]] have unwittingly furthered God's secret purposes by dressing Jesus up as a king.\"<ref>Robert J. Miller, ''The Complete Gospels'' (1994), p. 50</ref> In fact, the irony operates on two levels. [[James L. Resseguie]] points out that there is [[verbal irony]] in the way the soldiers \"mock Jesus as a dismal failure and a pretend king\" (that is, the soldiers are themselves being ironic) as well as [[dramatic irony]] in that the readers \"know that the acclamation rings true in ways that the soldiers could not possibly understand.\"<ref>[[James L. Resseguie]], [https://books.google.com/books?id=8JOdz84lmUQC&pg=PA74 Narrative Criticism of the New Testament: An Introduction] (2005), p. 74; see also \"A Glossary of New Testament Narrative Criticism with Illustrations, https://www.mdpi.com/2077-1444/10/3/217. </ref>  Luke 23:11 also mentions that \"[[Herod Antipas|Herod]] and his soldiers ridiculed and mocked him\" ([[New Revised Standard Version]]).\n\n==Third stage==\n[[File:Hendrick ter Brugghen - Die Verspottung Christi.jpg|thumb|left|[[Hendrick ter Brugghen]], ''The Mocking of Christ'', c. 1625]]\nJesus was also mocked while he was [[Crucifixion of Jesus|on the cross]]. According to Mark 15:29-30, this was done by those who passed by and hurled insults at him and told him to come down from the cross.  Mark 15:31-32 points out that \"the chief priests and the teachers of the law\" also mocked him among themselves, saying: \"He saved others, but he can\u2019t save himself! Let this Messiah, this king of Israel, come down now from the cross, that we may see and believe.\" Finally, those crucified with Jesus also heaped insults at him (Mark 15:32). \n\nLuke 23:36-37 mentions mocking by Roman soldiers: \"The soldiers also mocked him, coming up and offering him sour wine, and saying, 'If you are the King of the Jews, save yourself!'\" ([[New Revised Standard Version]]). In Matthew 27:42 people, priest and the elders mock Jesus, and shout at him while he is hanging on the cross: \"He saved others; let Him save Himself if He is the Christ, the chosen of God.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://biblehub.com/matthew/27-42.htm|title= Matthew 27:42|publisher=Bible Hub|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Luke 23:39, one criminal on his left who hung there together with Jesus on the cross, hurled insults at Jesus: \"Aren't you the Messiah? Save yourself and us!\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Luke+23|title=The Crucifixion of Jesus, Luke 23 |publisher=Bible Gateway|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nThus, whereas the first stage involves mockery by Jews, and the second stage mockery by gentiles, the third stage has both together.<ref>[[Klaas Schilder]], ''Christ on Trial'' (1939), p. 177.</ref> Leithart notes that at this point \"Jews and Gentiles, governors and criminals, scribes and commoners, all humanity joins in a single chorus of blasphemy.\"<ref name=Leithart />\n\nTimothy C. Gray notes that in the Gospel of Mark, the mocking of Jesus on the cross \"takes up the two charges leveled against Jesus at his trial\": firstly, that Jesus \"threatened the temple with destruction\" (14:58 and 15:29); secondly, that Jesus \"claimed to be the Messiah\" (14:61-62 and 15:31-32).<ref>Timothy C. Gray, ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=IINN-m6YIGMC&pg=PA181 The Temple in the Gospel of Mark: A Study in Its Narrative Role]'' (2008), p. 181.</ref>  {{Clear}}\n\n==Theological significance==\n[[File:Mateo Cerezo d. J. 001.jpg|thumb|upright=0.1|[[Mateo Cerezo]], ''[[Ecce Homo]]'', 1650]]\n{{Death of Jesus}}\n\n[[Peter Leithart]] argues that in the person of Jesus, God himself was mocked. He suggests that \"for Matthew, the cross is mainly about man\u2019s mockery of God,\" and notes that while Paul says in [[Epistle to the Galatians|Galatians]] 6:7 that \"God is not mocked\", this is precisely because God ''has'' been mocked.<ref name=Leithart />\n\nMany Christians see Jesus' suffering as being [[Redemption (theology)|redemptive]]. Francis Foulkes argues that the emphasis in the New Testament is on Jesus' suffering and death being \"for us\".<ref>Francis Foulkes, [http://www.biblestudytools.com/dictionaries/bakers-evangelical-dictionary/death-of-christ.html Death of Christ], ''Baker's Evangelical Dictionary of Biblical Theology''.</ref> In this way, some Christians see the mockery that Jesus endured as being borne on their behalf. For example, [[Philip Bliss]] wrote in his hymn, \"Hallelujah! What a Savior\":\n<blockquote><poem>\nBearing shame and scoffing rude,\nIn my place condemned He stood;\nSealed my pardon with His blood.\nHallelujah! What a Savior!<ref>[http://www.hymntime.com/tch/htm/h/a/l/halwasav.htm The Cyber Hymnal: ''Hallelujah! What a Savior'']</ref>\n</poem></blockquote>\n\nThe mockery of Jesus is also seen by many Christians in the servant songs,  such as in Isaiah 50:6  where \n<blockquote><poem>\nI gave my back to those who strike,\nand my cheeks to those who pull out the beard;\nI hid not my face  from disgrace and spitting.\n</poem></blockquote>\n\nWhich is in remarkable contrast with the forward looking following verse, Isaiah 50:7\n<blockquote><poem>\nBecause the Sovereign Lord helps me,\nI will not be disgraced.\nTherefore have I set my face like flint,\nand I know I will not be put to shame.\n</poem></blockquote>\n\nThe scene when Jesus was mocked while he was on the cross, is also a manifestation of the mercy of God through Jesus, who himself is mocked, humiliated and in pain. Two men were crucified at the same time as Jesus, one on his right hand and one on his left ({{Bibleverse||Matthew|27:38|KJV}}, {{Bibleverse||Mark|15:27-28,32|KJV}}, {{Bibleverse||Luke|23:33|KJV}}, {{Bibleverse||John|19:18|KJV}}), which [[Gospel of Mark|Mark]] interprets as fulfillment of the [[prophecy]] of [[Isaiah]] {{Bibleverse-nb||Isaiah|53:12|HE}}. According to [[Gospel of Matthew|Matthew]] and Mark, respectively, both of the \"thieves\" mocked Jesus ({{Bibleverse||Matthew|27:44|KJV}}, {{Bibleverse||Mark|15:32|KJV}}); Luke however, mentions that:\n<blockquote>\n<sup>39</sup> Now one of the criminals hanging there reviled Jesus, saying, \"Are you not the Messiah? Save yourself and us.\"\n<sup>40</sup> The other, however, rebuking him, said in reply, \"Have you no fear of God, for you are subject to the same condemnation?\n<sup>41</sup> And indeed, we have been condemned justly, for the sentence we received corresponds to our crimes, but this man has done nothing criminal.\"\n<sup>42</sup> Then he said, \"Jesus, remember me when you come into your kingdom.\"\n<sup>43</sup> He replied to him, \"Amen I say to you today you will be with me in Paradise.\" {{Bibleverse-nb||Luke|23:39-43|NIV}}\n</blockquote>\n\nJesus promised to [[Penitent thief|this thief]] that he will be with him in the Paradise, right in front of those who were mocking him. God saves through Jesus, because God is full of mercy, a mercy revealed through Jesus Christ, that says to a thief: \"Today you will be with me in Paradise.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.beliefnet.com/columnists/markdroberts/2007/04/the-eleventh-station-jesus-promises-his-kingdom-to-the-good-thief.html|title=The Eleventh Station: Jesus Promises His Kingdom to the Good Thief|publisher=Beliefnet|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Flagellation of Christ]]\n*[[Crown of thorns]]\n*[[Ecce homo]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite journal |last=Pejovi\u0107 |first=Roksanda |title=The Mocking of Christ and other scenes from the cycle of <i>The sufferings of Christ</i> as illustrated by musical instruments in southern-European art |journal=New Sound |issue=2 |date=1993 |pages=71\u201393 |issn=0354-818X }}\n* {{cite journal |last=Ballester |first=Jordi |title=Trumpets, Heralds and Minstrels: Their relation to the Image of Power and Representation in the Fourteenth- and Fifteenth-Century Catalano-Aragonese Painting |journal=Music in Art |volume=43 |issue=1\u20132 |date=2018 |pages=5\u201319 |issn=1522-7464 }}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline|Mocking of Christ}}\n\n[[Category:Passion of Jesus]]\n", "name_user": "71.15.193.215", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mocking_of_Jesus"}
{"title_page": "Journal", "text_new": "{{wikt}}\nA '''journal''', from the [[Old French]] ''journal'' (meaning \"daily\"), may refer to several things. In its original meaning, it refers to a daily [[record (disambiguation)|record]] of activities, but the term has evolved to mean any record of activities, regardless of time elapsed between entries, such as a\n*[[Diary]], a record of what happened over the course of a day or other period\n*[[Daybook]], also known as ''general journal'', a daily record of financial transactions\n*[[Logbook]], a record of events important to the operation of a vehicle, facility, or otherwise\n*[[Transaction log|Transaction journal]], a chronological record of data processing\nIn publishing, it can also refer to various [[periodical]]s or [[serial (publishing)|serials]]:\n*[[Academic journal]], a generic term referring to academic and scholarly periodicals in general\n**[[Scientific journal]], an academic journal focusing on science\n**[[Medical journal]], an academic journal focusing on medicine\n*[[Magazine]], a generic catch-all term referring to non-academic or scholarly periodicals in general\n**[[Trade magazine]], a magazine of interest to those of a particular profession or trade\n**[[Literary magazine]], a magazine devoted to literature in a broad sense\n*[[Newspaper]], a periodical covering general news and current events in politics, business, sports and art\n**[[Gazette]], a type of newspaper, often a newspaper of record\n**[[Government gazette]], a government newspaper which publishes public or legal notices\n\n'''Journal''' may also refer to:\n\n==Arts and entertainment==\n*[[Journal (Canadian TV series)|''Journal'' (Canadian TV series)]], a 1977 Canadian short film television series\n*[[Journal (German TV programme)|''Journal'' (German TV programme)]], a 1992\u20132015 German news programme that aired on Deutsche Welle\n*[[Journals (album)|''Journals'' (album)]], 2013 album by Justin Bieber \n*[[Journals (Cobain)|''Journals'' (Cobain)]], 2002 collection by Kurt Cobain\n\n==Other uses==\n*[[Journal (mechanical device)]], the section of a shaft that turns in a bearing\n*[[Journal entry]], an accounting transaction in the double-entry bookkeeping system\n*[[Journal Peaks]], Palmer Land, Antarctica\n\n==See also==\n*[[The Journal (disambiguation)|''The Journal'' (disambiguation)]], several publications and TV programs that carry this name\n*[[List of journals (disambiguation)]]\n\n{{Disambiguation}}\n", "text_old": "A '''journal''', from the [[Old French]] ''journal'' (meaning \"daily\"), may refer to several things. In its original meaning, it refers to a daily [[record (disambiguation)|record]] of activities, but the term has evolved to mean any record of activities, regardless of time elapsed between entries, such as a\n*[[Diary]], a record of what happened over the course of a day or other period\n*[[Daybook]], also known as ''general journal'', a daily record of financial transactions\n*[[Logbook]], a record of events important to the operation of a vehicle, facility, or otherwise\n*[[Transaction log|Transaction journal]], a chronological record of data processing\nIn publishing, it can also refer to various [[periodical]]s or [[serial (publishing)|serials]]:\n*[[Academic journal]], a generic term referring to academic and scholarly periodicals in general\n**[[Scientific journal]], an academic journal focusing on science\n**[[Medical journal]], an academic journal focusing on medicine\n*[[Magazine]], a generic catch-all term referring to non-academic or scholarly periodicals in general\n**[[Trade magazine]], a magazine of interest to those of a particular profession or trade\n**[[Literary magazine]], a magazine devoted to literature in a broad sense\n*[[Newspaper]], a periodical covering general news and current events in politics, business, sports and art\n**[[Gazette]], a type of newspaper, often a newspaper of record\n**[[Government gazette]], a government newspaper which publish